## 3️⃣ How to compile & link

Assuming the two files are named `blocksci.mli` and `blocksci_stubs.c`, and that
BlockSci’s headers are in `/usr/local/include/blocksci` and the library is
`-lblocksci`, the build with **OCaml 5.x** (or any recent version) looks like:

```sh
# Compile the C++ stub (need a C++ compiler)
g++ -std=c++17 -I/usr/local/include/blocksci \
    -c -o blocksci_stubs.o blocksci_stubs.c

# Build the OCaml library (static archive)
ocamlopt -c blocksci.mli
ocamlopt -c blocksci.ml          # (empty .ml that just does `external` bindings)

# Archive the object files
ocamlopt -a -o libblocksci.cmxa \
    blocksci.cmx blocksci_stubs.o -cclib -lblocksci

# Example usage (test.ml)
# -------------------------------------------------
# let () =
#   Blocksci.iter_blocks (fun b ->
#     Printf.printf "Height %d, %s, %Ld, %d txs\n%!"
#       b.Blocksci.height b.Blocksci.hash b.Blocksci.timestamp b.Blocksci.tx_count)
#
# -------------------------------------------------
# Compile the test program:
ocamlopt -I . -o test.native libblocksci.cmxa test.ml
```

If you use **Dune**, the `dune` file would look like:

```dune
(library
 (name blocksci)
 (public_name blocksci)
 (foreign_stubs
  (language c)
  (names blocksci_stubs)
  (flags (:standard -std=c++17))
  (include_dirs /usr/local/include/blocksci))
 (c_library_flags -lblocksci))
```

Now `ocamlfind` (or `dune`) will expose the `Blocksci` module with the
functions defined in the `.mli`.

